data.raw: Welcome Engineering Students! Quick Guide to Engineering Information Technology Resources Computer Lab information Want to know where the Engineering labs are? Want to see if a lab has open seats before walking around campu Visit our site at Keep Your Computer Labs Clean! Take pride in your computer labs! Please pickup after yourself and keep the labs clean for you and everyone else. As always, there is NO FOOD OR DRINK allowed in computer lab Lost and Found If you lose an item in one of the computer labs or need to turn in a lost item, please visit one of our Lost and Found location 2071 Black Engineering, 2215 Coover Hall, 2240 Hoover Hall, and 1200 Howe Hall. Remember to write your name on calculators and other items of value so they can be easily identified if lost. We will require proof before returning lost item Printing As an Engineering student you receive 4,000 print units per semester. Black and white printing is 5 units per side and color is 15 units per side. Lab computers automatically have local printers added. You are also able to print from a personal computer using Papercut Web Print or Google Print. Please visit and for detail Remote Acce Many of the applications available in the computer labs are also available remotely using your own computer. Please visit for more details and instructions on how to connect. CyBox ISU offers all students unlimited storage through a partnership with called CyBox. Visit for detail Personal Drive Please note it is limited to 10 GB. Microsoft Office and Engineering applications for FREE! For a list of titles, visit our IT portal at Departmental Specific Resources Did you know each major has their own dedicated IT staff? Check with your departmental IT staff for information about unique resources available to your major. Other Question All this information and more can be found at . If you have any other questions, please fill out our contact form located at Please remember when contacting us that your ISU e-mail addre is the most important piece of information we need about you. Your University ID (9-digit number) is not needed. Distributed by Engineering Technology Support. Copyright © 2018, Iowa State University of Science and Technology. All rights reserved. data.raw: September Undergraduate Newsletter Curriculum Corner Welcome back from all of us in Student Services! We are trying to meet as many of you as possible in the first 10 days of classes to make sure everything is set for your semester! If it is like the summer—it will whiz by! 1) Please note that we will be celebrating Scholars’ Fair on Tuesday, Sept. 11, from 5:30 p.m. – 7 p.m. Please join us in the excitement of student organization membership, faculty and grad student research and lots of giveaway 2) Welcome Dr Mai Zheng and Mohamed Selim as new computer engineering faculty members! You’ll probably see them in the hallways of Coover. 3) Remember that appointments can be made on AccessPlus . 4) As you think of spring semester, we will be teaching EE 439, EE 425x and Cpr E/EE 503X (see the experimental course list 5) If you are still looking for a part-time job, Vicky is trying to find an undergrad TAs for Engr 160, Cpr E 381, EE/Cpr E 294 and 394 Undergraduate Circuit First FAN Club meeting of the year, 9/28 - FREE PIZZA!!! Want to be a part of something more Join one of our student orgs! From solar decatholons to engineering ambassadors, we have so much for you!! Click here to see all our student organization  Don't forget about all of our opportunities to better your chances of scoring a job at the career fair! Study Abroad Fair, Tuesday, Sept. 4 - Come and see ALL the places YOU can study in around the WORLD! Summer Sparks Check out some of the research and moments that happened over this summer!! McCune 1910 surveying notebook 1910 surveying notebook shows Iowa State’s campus through the eyes — and feet — of ECpE alum A notebook from ECpE alum Charles E McCune was recently discovered in Ohio by a woman with no ties to Iowa State. After returning the book to ISU, ECpE dives into the tale of Charles E. McCune. The nine lives of Mani Mina Mani Mina, an associate professor in industrial design and electrical and computer engineering in ECpE is very popular amongst students, alumni and faculty. From theater to history of science, Mina has a broad range of studies that he was reeled into when he was in college. ECpE engineer published for Alzheimer’s-testing device Present in the lives of millions, Alzheimer disease is a prominent concern throughout the world. Long Que , associate professor and researcher in the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering at Iowa State University , has recently developed a device that can determine if a person potentially has Alzheimer’s disease along with Dr. Pan Deng, a neurologist and Chao Song, a PhD student in electrical engineering. Students compete in PrISUm - following the Oregon Trail With a mission to change transportation, PrISUm was along for the ride with other students from around the nation this summer, following the Oregon Trail. Read about the student favorite part of PrISUm - and advice if you'd like to join. Tech Buzz Computer program looks 5 minutes into the future As humans, we are usually fairly accurate when predicting what another person will do next. Bur for computers, predicting a human actions has been a challenge - until now. This computer is a chef perfect partner, foreshadowing when to grab some ingredients and what ingredients to grab - without a single command! Seminars and Events Sept. 6, 10 a.m. - John Deere Day at Iowa State University Sept. 11, 5:30 p.m. - ECpE Scholar Fair Sept. 18, 12 p.m. - Iowa State University Engineering Career Fair Sept. 25, 12 p.m. - Iowa State University Engineering Career Fair Sept. 28, 11 a.m. - FAN Club John Deere Day Happy September! Check out our socials! data.raw: Jack, Hi! What: this semester’s first meeting of the Alliance for Disability Awarene (ADA) When: Wednesday August 29, 2018 at 5:00 PM (feel free to come late!) Where: the lobby of the Student Services Building More info: You are invited to this semester’s first meeting of the Alliance for Disability Awarene (ADA) a student organization on campus dedicated to supporting students with disabilities, as well as raising awarene for the wide variety of disabilities on campus and pushing for a more accessible ISU. This year the club has new presidential leadership of myself, Lauren Berglund and Brittni Wendling and we hope to increase student involvement through fun gatherings and activitie Please join us for pizza, conversation, and more! If you have any questions or need for accommodations, please feel free to email either myself at and/or Brittni at We hope to see you there! The ADA leadership team, Brittni Wendling (co-president) Lauren Berglund (co-president) + Sheba Leland Smith (vice-president) Amber Markley (social chair) Lauren Berglund Child, Adult, and Family Services | Iowa State University Student Assistant | Student Accessibility Services President | Alliance for Disability Awareness
